│ The `trunc` instruction truncates the high-order bits of its operand to fit the         │
│ destination type. If the `nuw` (no unsigned wrap) or `nsw` (no signed wrap) keywords    │
│ are present, the instruction can produce a `poison` value under certain conditions.     │
│ Specifically:                                                                           │
│                                                                                         │
│ - `nuw`: If any of the truncated bits are non-zero, the result is `poison`.             │
│ - `nsw`: If any of the truncated bits are not the same as the top bit of the truncation │
│ result, the result is `poison`.                                                         │
│                                                                                         │
│ The test failure suggests that the transformation introduces `nuw` and `nsw` flags to   │
│ the `trunc` instruction, which may lead to `poison` values if the assumptions about the │
│ operand are incorrect. To address this, I will remove the `nuw` and `nsw` flags from    │
│ the `trunc` instruction in the transformation pipeline to ensure that it does not       │
│ produce `poison` values.                                                                │
